aa(lp301
VThere was a case study done in 1960s Britain,
p302
aVwhen they were moving from grammar schools to comprehensive schools.
p303
aVIt's called the streaming trials. We call it "tracking" here in the States.
p304
aVIt's separating students from A, B, C, D and so on.
p305
aVAnd the "A students" get the tougher curriculum, the best teachers, etc.
p306
aVWell, they took, over a three-month period,
p307
aVD-level students, gave them A's,
p308
aVtold them they were "A's," told them they were bright,
p309
aVand at the end of this three-month period,
p310
aVthey were performing at A-level.
p311
aa(lp312
VAnd, of course, the heartbreaking, flip side of this study,
p313
aVis that they took the "A students" and told them they were "D's."
p314
aVAnd that's what happened at the end of that three-month period.
p315
aVThose who were still around in school, besides the people who had dropped out.
p316
aVA crucial part of this case study was that the teachers were duped too.
p317
aVThe teachers didn't know a switch had been made.
p318
aVThey were simply told, "These are the 'A-students,' these are the 'D-students.'"
p319
aVAnd that's how they went about teaching them and treating them.
